rename.from: Allow 64 bit floating point integer types
rename.to: Allow 64 bit floating point number types

body: Does the original one use float64 ?

That's correct, the original model is using float64. I was given some inputs and outputs from the original model and given an exported onnx version of the model. When I ran a test for the inputs and outputs I saw some deviations. From some trial and error investigations we discovered that the large weights of the model were probably the cause as they would probably contribute to rounding errors. As mentioned, reducing the weights of the model reduced the difference between onnxruntime output and the original model predictions generated in scikit. I believe supporting float64 would eliminate the rounding errors because it would be the same data type as supported with other model frameworks.
Would you please share me the converted model or give me a full list of ONNX operators it contains?

Hi, here's the chain of ONNX operators it contains in order.

-> float_input 1 x 19
-> Cast
-> MatMul 19 x 5
-> Add 1 x 5
-> Relu
-> MatMul 5 x 1
-> Add 1 x 1
-> Identity
-> Reshape
-> Variable 1 x 1 (output)
Please let me know if this is sufficient or you require more details. Thanks.
Some of them are not ONNX operators.

Couple of questions:

1) Why do you need to know the operators?
2) Is there any way I can get the operators from the ONNX file? I used a visualization tool (https://github.com/lutzroeder/netron) to open the ONNX file and listed out the listed operators, however I'm not sure where the non ONNX operators would have come from.

I would have thought the scenario is fairly obvious and exists regardless of what operations my model has, correct me if I'm wrong. Doesn't only allowing 32bit floats inherently limit the range of values that a model can use? Is there some work around?

Below are the Operators we currently support:
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/master/docs/OperatorKernels.md

Some of them doesn't support double, even the ONNX spec says it should. 

So, please give me a list of the ONNX Operators you need, I'll help to implement them.

-> Cast
-> MatMul 19 x 5
-> Add 1 x 5
-> Relu
-> MatMul 5 x 1
-> Add 1 x 1
-> Identity
-> Reshape

Are all ONNX listed in the link you gave me. I think there was some confusion as the first and last elements in the prior list I gave you were just the names of the input and output variables. They're not operators and can be ignored.

So basically I need all of the operators listed in this post.
